tion at the National Gallery of Canada in 2006, many Canadians knew almost nothing about Morrisseau’s work. Using discourse analysis methods, Robertson looks at news stories, magazine articles, and film footage, ranging from Morrisseau’s first solo exhibition at Toronto’s Pollock Gallery in 1962 until his death in 2007 to examine the cultural assumptions that have framed Morrisseau.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt autochtonexCouverture de pressexCanada. 0aArtistes autochtonesxCouverture de pressexCanada. 0aArtistes autochtonesxOpinion publiquexCanada. 0aAutochtonesxCouverture de pressexCanada. 0aIndian artistsxPress coveragezCanada. 0aIndian artistszCanadaxPublic opinion. 0aIndigenous artxPress coveragezCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxPress coveragezCanada. 0aNative artxPress coveragexCanada. 0aNative artistsxPress coveragexCanada. 0aNative artistsxPublic opinionxCanada. 0aNative peoplesxPress coveragexCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755501540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887555015423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887555015/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles